 corporation, Hypatia Inc..\n\n.\n\n'''''Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy''''' is a [[peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] published quarterly by [[Cambridge University Press]]As of January of 2019, the journal is led by co-editors [[Bonnie Mann|Bonnie J. Mann]], [https://nam01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fhypatiaphilosophy.org%2Fabout%2Feditors%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cn01423414%40unf.edu%7C8ea5c7291489477e625e08d7d7ec2efc%7Cdf29b2fa8929482f9dbb60ff4df224c4%7C1%7C0%7C637215281774015074&amp;sdata=OKTSeDVIudXvqSf2OmuMov9gtdsSqyiFFwUgh3wymjE%3D&amp;reserved=0 Erin McKenna], [https://nam01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fhypatiaphilosophy.org%2Fabout%2Feditors%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cn01423414%40unf.edu%7C8ea5c7291489477e625e08d7d7ec2efc%7Cdf29b2fa8929482f9dbb60ff4df224c4%7C1%7C0%7C637215281774015074&amp;sdata=OKTSeDVIudXvqSf2OmuMov9gtdsSqyiFFwUgh3wymjE%3D&amp;reserved=0 Camisha Russell], and [https://nam01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fhypatiaphilosophy.org%2Fabout%2Feditors%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cn01423414%40unf.edu%7C8ea5c7291489477e625e08d7d7ec2efc%7Cdf29b2fa8929482f9dbb60ff4df224c4%7C1%7C0%7C637215281774015074&amp;sdata=OKTSeDVIudXvqSf2OmuMov9gtdsSqyiFFwUgh3wymjE%3D&amp;reserved=0 Roc\u00edo Zambrana]. Book reviews are published by ''[https://www.hypatiareviews.org/ Hypatia Reviews Online (HRO)]''. [https://www.hypatiareviews.org/ HRO] is edited by [http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/editors/ Erin McKenna] and [http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/editors/ Joan Woolfrey]. The journal is owned by a non-profit corporation, Hypatia, Inc.<ref name=\"ProPublica\">{{cite web|url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/262868769|title=Hypatia Inc|publisher=ProPublica|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200312010041/https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/262868769|archivedate=12 March 2020}}</ref>The idea for the journal arose out of meetings of the [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] (SWIP)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Trebilcot |first1=Joyce |editor1-last=al-Hibri |editor1-first=Azizah Y. |editor2-last=Simons |editor2-first=Margaret A. |editor1-link=Azizah Y. al-Hibri |title=Hypatia Reborn: Essays in Feminist Philosophy |date=1990 |publisher=Indiana University Press |location=Bloomington and Indianapolis |isbn=0-253-32744-X |chapter=Foreword |pages=ix\u2013x |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy | url = http://pembroke-archives.squarespace.com/hypatia-a-journal-of-feminist-philosophy-1/ | publisher = [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] | access-date = 29 March 2018}}</ref> in the 1970s.Philosopher and legal scholar [[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]] became the founding editor in 1982, when it was published as a \"piggy back\" issue of the [[Women's Studies International Forum|''Women's Studies International Forum'']].<ref name=\"Hibri22Oct2009\">{{cite news|last1=Al-Hibri|first1=Azizah Y|url=https://vimeo.com/12221774|title=A Journal of Her Own: Hypatia Founders and Editors|date=22 October 2009|publisher=25th Anniversary Conference: Feminist Legacies/Feminist Futures, University of Washington|at=Courtesy of Vimeo, 00:05:50\u201300:08:15|ref=harv|author-link=Azizah Y. al-Hibri}}</ref> Named after [[Hypatia of Alexandria]], a philosopher who was murdered by a mob in 415 CE, it became an independent journal in 1986.<ref name=\"Gruen2010\">{{cite journal |last1=Gruen |first1=Lori |author-link1=Lori Gruen|last2=Wylie|first2=Alison |author-link2=Alison Wylie|title=Feminist Legacies/Feminist Futures: 25th Anniversary Special Issue\u2014Editors' Introduction |journal=Hypatia |date=Fall 2010 |volume=25 |issue=4 |pages=725\u2013732|jstor=40928652|doi=10.1111/j.1527-2001.2010.01141.x }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Background===\n{{See also|Feminist philosophy}}\n''&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Hypatia'' has its roots in regional meetings of the [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] (SWIP), established in 1972. One of SWIP's earliest ideas was that it would set up a philosophy journal.<ref name=\"Gruen2010\" /> The thought of \"[[A Room of One's Own|a journal of our own\"]] was very powerful, according to Kathryn Morgan ([[University of Toronto|Toronto]]), speaking in 2009 on the history of ''Hypatia''.<ref name=\"Hibri22Oct2009\" /> At the time, according to [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] ([[City University of New York|CUNY]]), president of the Hypatia Inc. board of directors since February 2018,<ref name=\"search23Feb2018\">{{cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/announcements/announcement-hypatias-board-directors-task-force-co-chairs/|title=Announcement from Hypatia's Board of Directors and Task Force Co-Chairs|date=23 February 2018|publisher=Hypatia|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164503/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/announcements/announcement-hypatias-board-directors-task-force-co-chairs/|archivedate=1 March 2018}}</ref> philosophers who wanted to write about gender-related issues were being silenced in a discipline \"riven by unabashed bias and vested interest, inflicting its own form of unapologetic mob violence\".<ref name=\"Alcoff4May2017\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/lsalcoff/posts/10156108465053047|title=Here's my take.|last1=Alcoff|first1=Linda Mart\u00edn|author-link=Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff|date=4 May 2017|publisher=Facebook|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170515200503/https://www.facebook.com/lsalcoff/posts/10156108465053047|archivedate=15 May 2017|access-date=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Azizah Y. al-Hibri, 2012.jpeg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|[[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]], 2012]]&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; SWIP decided in 1977 to set up an [[editorial board]] to plan the journal; the first board was put together by [[Ann Garry]] ([[California State University, Los Angeles|Cal State LA]]) and Jacqueline Thomason ([[University of Massachusetts Amherst|UMass Amherst]]).<ref name=\"Gruen2010\" /> At a meeting in Denver in the spring of 1979, the board agreed that [[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]] ([[University of Richmond|UR]]) should be the founding editor.<ref name=\"Gruen2010\" /> Al-Hibri began work on the journal in 1982, after she had completed her PhD in philosophy and just as she was starting her first year of [[law school]].<ref name=\"Hibri22Oct2009\" /> The philosophy and women's studies departments at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] offered support in the form of an office and research assistance.<ref name=\"Interview 00:08:45\">{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/13360820|title=Interview with Hypatia Founders and Editors|date=24 October 2009|publisher=25th Anniversary Conference: Feminist Legacies/Feminist Futures, University of Washington|at=From 00:08:45|ref={{sfnref|25th Anniversary Conference|2009}}}}</ref> [[Women's Studies International Forum|''Women's Studies International Forum'']] agreed to publish the new journal as an annual \"piggy back\" issue of its own, which it did for three years,<ref name=\"Hibri22Oct2009\" /> and distributed 10,000 brochures to its mailing list advertising it.\n\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; The group led by Al-Hibri decided that submissions would be fully reviewed and that substantive comments would be offered, Alcoff wrote, rather than the usual brief rejection, to help authors improve their work and to contribute to the field's development.<ref name=\"Alcoff4May2017\" /> Donna Serniak ([[University of Pennsylvania|Penn]]) was responsible for the first issue. It was first published independently of ''Women's Studies International Forum'' in 1986.<ref name=\"Gruen2010\" />\n\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; The journal is named after [[Hypatia of Alexandria]], a mathematician and philosopher who was murdered by a mob in 415 CE. Al-Hibri said that the SWIP editorial board chose the name to reflect that women have \"deep roots in philosophy\".<ref name=\"Interview 00:08:45\" /> According to [[Linda L\u00f3pez McAlister]] ([[University of South Florida|USF]]), the idea for the name came from Sue Larson ([[Barnard College|Barnard]]) during a meeting of Eastern SWIP in 1973. [[Sandra Harding]] ([[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]), who was at the meeting, objected, thinking it awful to name a feminist-philosophy journal after a woman who had been \"stoned to death for telling the truth\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Al-Hibri|first1=Azizah Y.|date=Spring 2013|title=Hypatia's Birth: It Took a Village|journal=Hypatia|volume=28|issue=2|pages=399\u2013403|jstor=24542133|ref=harv|author-link1=Azizah Y. al-Hibri}}</ref> {{sfn|25th Anniversary Conference|2009|loc=00:02:50}}The first suggestion was ''Hypatia: A Journal of Philosophy and Feminism'', rather than ''A Journal of Feminist Philosophy'', because at the time it was unclear what feminist philosophy might be.<ref name=\":1\">{{harvnb||Al-Hibri|2013|p=401}}; {{harvnb|Al-Hibri|2009|loc=from 00:08:57}}.</ref>\n\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Throughout Hypatia\u2019s thirty-three-year history, the journal has been influential in legitimizing feminist philosophy within the field. It has served as one of the most pivotal sources of scholarship in feminist philosophy, both because it showcases a wide range of feminist viewpoints and because it has self-consciously addressed varied views and issues in the discipline. In a editorial statement titled \u201cThe Promise of Feminist Philosophy,\u201d the editors note that:\n<br /><blockquote>Hypatia\u2019s specific history in this regard is complex. The journal\u2019s editors have often addressed questions of disciplinary pluralism, demographic exclusion and marginalization, and the journal\u2019s own role in setting the agenda for feminist agitation or compliance within the academy...The special issue structure has sometimes allowed ''Hypatia'' to create space for scholars who are subjected to the most persistent forms of marginalization in the discipline, and for intersectional feminist work, even as ''Hypatia'' as a whole has been justly criticized for the underrepresentation of such work<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Mann|first=Bonnie|last2=McKenna|first2=Erin|last3=Russell|first3=Camisha|last4=Zambrana|first4=Roc\u00edo|date=|title=The Promise of Feminist Philosophy|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/hypatia/article/promise-of-feminist-philosophy/5AD1859F6B6C29F76676169B0C5CC557|journal=Hypatia|language=en|volume=34|issue=3|pages=394\u2013400|doi=10.1111/hypa.12490|issn=0887-5367|via=}}</ref>....More recently, the development of ''Hypatia'' clusters (a set of two or more articles on a single theme in an open issue) offers another avenue that might be employed to highlight work that is marginalized in the larger discipline. </blockquote>\n\n=== 2017 Controversy ===\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; In 2017, Hypatia became involved in a [[Hypatia transracialism controversy|controversy]] concerning the publication of an article titled, \u201cIn Defense of Transracialism,\u201d authored by Rebecca Tuvel. Comparing the case of Caitlyn Jenner to that of Rachel Dolezal, Tuvel argued that \"[s]ince we should accept transgender individuals' decisions to change sexes, we should also accept transracial individuals' decisions to change races.\"<ref name=\"Singal2May2017\">{{cite news|last=Singal|first=Jesse|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/05/transracialism-article-controversy.html|title=This Is What a Modern-Day Witch Hunt Looks Like|date=2 May 2017|work=New York Magazine}}</ref><ref name=\"Weinberg1May2017\">{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/05/01/philosophers-article-transracialism-sparks-controversy/|title=Philosopher's Article On Transracialism Sparks Controversy (Updated with response from author)|date=1 May 2017|work=Daily Nous}}</ref> Tuvel\u2019s claims and citational practices were widely criticized within the feminist community.<ref name=\"HypatiaCUPMarch2020\" /> The article also engaged in a practice commonly known as \u2018[[Transphobia|deadnaming]],\u2019 i.e., \u201cusing a pre-transition name for someone instead of a post-transition one,\u201d which is widely considered a non-affirming practice in the trans and queer community; the name was amended after publication. Some critics of the article argued that practices such as these could have been prevented by engaging with the work of trans philosophers and the substantial literature on trans philosophy.<ref name=\"HypatiaCUPMarch2020\" /> Other critics have suggested that further engagement with black feminist and black feminist scholars was equally necessary.<ref name=\":2\" /> The journal\u2019s current editorial team has issued a brief guide for editors, contributors, and reviewers outlining best citational practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypatiaphilosophy.org/publication-ethics/|title=publication ethics|website=hypatia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Criticisms were voiced through both more official channels (for example, in an open letter to the journal) and informally on social media platforms such as Facebook and Twitter.<ref name=\"letter\">{{cite news|url=https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1efp9C0MHch_6Kfgtlm0PZ76nirWtcEsqWHcvgidl2mU/viewform?ts=59066d20&edit_requested=true|title=Open letter to Hypatia|access-date=3 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170502164603/https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1efp9C0MHch_6Kfgtlm0PZ76nirWtcEsqWHcvgidl2mU/viewform?ts=59066d20&edit_requested=true|archivedate=2 May 2017|publisher=Google Docs}}</ref> The journal distanced itself further from the article on May 1<sup>st</sup>, 2017 when a Hypatia associate editor apologized on the journal's Facebook page for the article's publication, on behalf of \"a majority of the Hypatia's Board of Associated Editors\".<ref name=\"Tuvel2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Tuvel|first1=Rebecca|date=25 April 2017|title=In Defense of Transracialism|journal=Hypatia|volume=32|issue=2|pages=263\u2013278|doi=10.1111/hypa.12327|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Oliver7May2017\">{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Kelly|url=http://thephilosophicalsalon.com/if-this-is-feminism-its-been-hijacked-by-the-thought-police/|title=If this is feminism|date=7 May 2017|work=The Philosophical Salon|publisher=Los Angeles Review of Books|author-link=Kelly Oliver}}</ref><ref name=\"Alcoff4May2017\" />The editor-in-chief, Sally Scholz (Villanova), stood by the article, and the board of directors, led by Miriam Solomon (Temple), confirmed that it would not be retracted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/honor-roll/editors-emeritae/|title=editors emeritae|website=hypatia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Communication between the governing bodies of the journal were in disagreement concerning the best approach toward the article and its subsequent controversy. \n\n\nIn July 2017 Scholz resigned as editor-in-chief, along with Shelley Wilcox, editor of ''Hypatia Reviews Online''. Subsequently, eight of the associate editors also resigned, stating that the current controversy was \"grounded in long-standing differences and tensions within the field.\" Following these resignations, the board of directors announced that a task force would restructure the journal's governance, and that anyone in an editorial or non-board position with Hypatia would be \"required to sign a statement of adherence to guidelines issued by COPE, the Committee on Publication Ethics\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tuvel|first=Rebecca|date=Winter 2018|title=Racial Transitions and Controversial Positions: Reply to Taylor, Gordon, Sealey, Hom, and Botts|url=https://www.pdcnet.org/C1257B82005A7B6C/file/A70140B8B305A70B8525826B006A6E2D/$FILE/philtoday_2018_0062_0001_0077_0092.pdf|journal=Philosophy Today|volume=62|issue=1|pages=(73\u201388), 74|doi=10.5840/philtoday2018223200}}</ref><ref name=\"letter\" /><ref name=\"Anderson18May2017\">{{cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|title=Statement From Hypatia Board|last1=Anderson|first1=Elizabeth|last2=Francis|first2=Leslie (Treasurer)|date=18 May 2017|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609221247/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|archivedate=9 June 2017|last3=Grasswick|first3=Heidi (Secretary)|last4=Solomon|first4=Miriam (President)|last5=Tessman|first5=Lisa (Chair)}}</ref> The board subsequently appointed interim editorial team made up of [[Ann Garry]] (Interim Editor), [[Serene Khader]] (Co-editor), [[Alison Stone]] (Co-edtitor) and Roc\u00edo Zambrana (Intrerim Co-Editor beginning in the fall of 2018). Joan Woolfrey and Simon Ruchti served as Interim Editors of Hypatia Reviews Online. Maja Sidzinska served as the Managing Editor for Hypatia Reviews Online. The interim editorial team worked to maintain the journal through July 1<sup>st</sup>, 2018. These teams also assisted the transition to the current editorial team. In November 2017 [[Sally Haslanger]] (MIT), Serene Khader, and Yannik Thiem (Villanova) were named as the governance task-force co-chairs. <ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"McKenzie6May2017\">{{cite news|last1=McKenzie|first1=Lindsay|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/A-Journal-Article-Provoked-a/240021|title=A Journal Article Provoked a Schism in Philosophy. Now the Rifts Are Deepening|date=6 May 2017|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|last2=Harris|first2=Adam|last3=Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z|first3=Fernanda}}</ref> The five-person board of directors was replaced in February 2018.<ref name=\"Weinberg13Nov2017\">{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/11/13/hypatia-board-announces-task-force/|title=Hypatia Board Announces Task Force|date=13 November 2017|work=Daily Nous}}</ref> [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] and Kim Q. Hall, two of the associate editors who resigned in July,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/hypatia.editorialoffice/posts/1852550825032876|title=To our friends and colleagues in feminist philosophy|last1=Heyes|first1=Cressida|date=1 May 2017|publisher=Hypatia{{'}}s Facebook page|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170501220930/https://www.facebook.com/hypatia.editorialoffice/posts/1852550825032876%23|archivedate=1 May 2017|access-date=25 May 2017}}</ref> became president of the board of directors and chair of the search committee for the new editorial team, respectivelyS The 2017 controversy has generated considerable scholarly reflection in debate, both within the pages of Hypatia and beyond. [FR][[Hypatia (journal)#%20ftn2|<sup><sup>[2]</sup></sup>]]\n\n==== Task Force ====\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; In July 2017 Scholz resigned as editor-in-chief, along with Shelley Wilcox, editor of ''Hypatia Reviews Online''. The board of directors announced that a task force would restructure the journal's governance, and that anyone in an editorial or non-board position with ''Hypatia'' would be \"required to sign a statement of adherence to guidelines issued by COPE, the [[Committee on Publication Ethics]]\". <ref name=\"resignation\">{{cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/statements/board-directors-statement-july-20-2017/|title=Board of Directors' Statement (July 20, 2017)|date=20 July 2017|website=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724105806/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/statements/board-directors-statement-july-20-2017/|archivedate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"interim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|title=Continuation of Interim Editorial Team|date=20 July 2017|publisher=Hypatia News|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043838/http://www.hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Weinberg3Aug2017\">{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/08/03/further-developments-at-hypatia/|title=Further Developments at Hypatia|date=3 August 2017|work=Daily Nous}}</ref>According to a statement from the associate editors, whose role was to choose the next editor, the board of directors asked them, on 17 July, to resign or the journal's governance documents would be suspended, which would remove the associate editors' influence. Eight of the associate editors resigned. In their resignation statement, they wrote that the current controversy was \"grounded in long-standing differences and tensions within the field.\" They argued that feminist philosophy had an ethical commitment to transform philosophy into \"a discipline that honors the perspectives and welcomes the scholarly contributions of historically marginalized groups, including people of color, trans* people, disabled people, and queer people.\"<ref name=\"Weinberg24July2017\">{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/07/24/hypatias-associate-editors-resign/|title=Hypatia's Associate Editors Resign|date=24 July 2017|work=Daily Nous}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Flaherty|first1=Colleen|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/07/24/divisions-within-hypatias-editorial-board-lead-resignations-top-editors|title=(Another) Shake-Up at 'Hypatia'|date=24 July 2017|work=Inside Higher Ed}}</ref><ref name=\"Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z21July2017\">{{cite news|last1=Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z|first1=Fernanda|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Months-After/240722|title=Months After 'Transracialism' Flap, Controversy Still Rages at Feminist Philosophy Journal|date=21 July 2017|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref>\n\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; The board appointed interim editors, and in November 2017 [[Sally Haslanger]] ([[MIT]]), Serene Khader, and Yannik Thiem (Villanova) were named as the governance task-force co-chairs.<ref name=\"Weinberg13Nov2017\" /><ref name=\"taskforce\">{{cite news|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/task-force/hypatia-board-directors-announces-task-force-co-chairs/|title=Hypatia Board of Directors Announces Task Force Co-Chairs|date=1 November 2017|work=Hypatia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724115800/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/task-force/hypatia-board-directors-announces-task-force-co-chairs/|archivedate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"EditorialBoardMarch2018\">{{cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/editorialboard/|title=Editorial board|date=1 March 2018|publisher=Hypatia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301224919/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/editorialboard/|archivedate=1 March 2018}}</ref>The five-person board of directors, including Solomon, was replaced in February 2018.<ref name=\"search23Feb2018\" /> Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff and Kim Hall, two of the associate editors who resigned in July,<ref name=\"Weinberg24July2017\" /> became president of the board of directors and chair of the search committee for the new editorial team, respectively.<ref name=\"search23Feb2018\" /><ref name=\"edandgovJuly2018\">{{cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/|title=Editorial and governance boards|website=Hypatia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724092156/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/|archivedate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 'Grievance Studies' Affair ===\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; During the search for a new editorial team, the journal was targeted by a group of authors who sought to highlight what they understood as \u201cpoor scholarship in several academic fields.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/feminist-philosophy-news/|title=news & archive|website=hypatia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> What has become known as the \u2018Grievance Studies Affair\u2019 targeted several journals in the humanities and social sciences, submitting articles under false identities. The article that was accepted was deliberately designed to satirize the vocabulary and practices of contemporary feminist philosophy. The fraudulent submission which was accepted, was revealed before the article could be published and never appeared in Hypatia.<ref name=\"Brubaker18May2017\">{{cite news|last1=Brubaker|first1=Rogers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/18/opinion/the-uproar-over-transracialism.html|title=The Uproar Over 'Transracialism'|date=18 May 2017|work=The New York Times|author-link=Rogers Brubaker}}</ref>\n\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; In October of 2018, the journal published a statement critically responding to the fraudulent submissions and, whilst denouncing the breakdown of trust in knowledge production and in academic publishing, committed to \u201crevisit[ing] our procedures to see whether we can better screen for fraud in ways that will burden neither the very authors we hope to encourage to submit their work nor the reviewers we ask to give their time to their important task.\u201d<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/statements/statement-concerning-fraudulent-submissions/|title=Statement Concerning Fraudulent Submissions|date=2018-10-17|website=hypatia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> The editors further emphasized that the hoaxers had manipulated Hypatia\u2019s publication and review practices which were intended to \u201cencourage submissions by younger and marginalized scholars\u201d and \u201cto avoid placing unnecessary hurdles in the way of submitting and revising manuscripts.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" /> Other critics of the Grievance Studies affair, such as Justin Weinberg, Associate Professor at the University of South Carolina, point out that if citations and descriptions of other scholars\u2019 work are accurate, the hoax does not reflect editorial discrepancies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailynous.com/2018/10/03/hypatia-journals-successfully-tricked-accepting-fake-papers/|title=Hypatia and other Journals Successfully Tricked Into Accepting \"Fake\" Papers (Updated)|last=Weinberg|first=Justin|date=2018-10-03|website=Daily Nous|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n\n==Governance==\n''Hypatia'' is owned by a non-profit corporation, Hypatia Inc.,<ref name=ProPublica/> registered in April 2008 in the State of Washington. The purpose of the non-profit is \"to foster feminist scholarship in philosophy and related fields, including through the publication of the academic journal ''Hypatia''\".{{efn|\"A non-profit corporation, Hypatia Inc. (WA), was registered in the state of Washington in April 2008. Its purpose, as stated in the articles of incorporation, is 'to foster feminist scholarship in philosophy and related fields, including through the publication of the academic journal Hypatia.'<ref name=governance>{{cite web|title=''Hypatia'' governance, adopted 26 June 2009 by the Hypatia editors and associate editors|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/pdfs/hypatia_governance.pdf|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043324/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/pdfs/hypatia_governance.pdf|archivedate=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} As of October 2019, the board of directors consisted of [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]], Talia Mae Bettcher, [[Ann Garry]], [[Helen Longino]], [[Jacqueline Scott]], and [[Nancy Tuana]]. In addition, the journal listed an international advisory board of 15 and an 11-strong board of associate editors. Instead of an editor-in-chief, four co-editors were named, [[Bonnie Mann|Bonnie J. Mann]], Erin McKenna, Camisha Russell, and Roc\u00edo Zambrana, and a managing editor, Sarah LaChance Adams. The managing editor of ''Hypatia Reviews Online'' was named as Bj\u00f8rn Kristensen.<ref name=governanceOct2019>{{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=hypatiaphilosophy.org |publisher=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018192940/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=18 October 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Previous editors-in-chief were:<ref name=HonorRoll>{{cite web|title=Hypatia Honor Roll|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/honor_roll_2013.html|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808112927/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/honor_roll_2013.html|archivedate=8 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=26em|\n* [[Azizah al-Hibri]] (1982\u20131984)\n* Margaret Simons (1984\u20131990)\n* [[Linda L\u00f3pez McAlister]] (1990\u20131998), with Cheryl Hall and Joanne Waugh (1995\u20131998)\n* [[Laurie Shrage|Laurie J. Shrage]] and [[Nancy Tuana]] (1998\u20132003)\n* [[Hilde Lindemann]] (2003\u20132008)\n* [[Lori Gruen]] (2008\u20132010) and [[Alison Wylie]] (2008\u20132013)\n* [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] and [[Ann Cudd]] (2010\u20132013)\n* [[Sally Scholz]] (2013\u20132017)\n* [[Ann Garry]] (interim editor, 2018\u20132019)\n}}\n\n=== <u>2018 Revised Governance Structure</u> ===\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Following the transition to the current editorial team in 2018, the governing bodies of Hypatia collaborated to produce a new governance document in order to facilitate open communication and procedural consistency in cases of conflict.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/hypatia-governance-structure/|title=hypatia governance structure|last=|first=|date=|website=Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The journal also now has two standing committees, the Reparative Response Committee and the Outreach and Ethics Committee, which serves as intermediary bodies in cases where conflict resolution or intra-organizational mediation is necessary. Each committee consists of members from the Non-Profit board, the Editorial Team, and the Associate Editors. The Reparative Response Committee is specifically tasked with meeting annually to monitor the internal operations of the journal and to facilitate communication if disputes arise. The Outreach and Ethics Committee is tasked with outreach, public engagement, and ethics. It will be responsible for addressing such things as hoax submissions, and complaints from authors. It will also engage in an ongoing reflection on Hypatia\u2019s ethical commitments, ensuring that all those involved with Hypatia are aware of, and adhere to, the COPE guidelines. This committee is also responsible for producing an annual report identifying strengths, successes, challenges, and suggestions for improvement in the journals operation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n\nIn February 2020, Hypatia\u2019s governance boards elected a new Board of Associate Editors<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/uncategorized/793/|title=Announcing New Associate Editors|last=|first=|date=February 21, 2020|website=Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>, including:\n\n* Mar\u00eda del Rosario Acosta L\u00f3pez\n* Saray Ayala-Lopez\n* Talia Bettcher\n* [[Ann Cudd]] \n* Vrinda Dalmiya\n* Ver\u00f3nica Gago\n* Dilek Huseyinzadegan\n* Qrescent Mali Mason\n* Krushil Watene\n* Yolonda Wilson\n* Robin Zheng\n\n== Diversity Grants & Essay Prizes ==\n'''&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;''' Beginning 2014, Hypatia began its Diversity in [http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/hypatia-resources/hypatia-diversity-grants/ Feminist Philosophy Grant] program. Offering both individual and project funding opportunities, the diversity grant is an expression of the journal\u2019s commitment to supporting both scholarship on diversity issues in feminist philosophy as well as scholars from groups traditionally underrepresented within the profession of philosophy. In 2018, the Diversity Project Grants were awarded to:<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Hypatia 2018 Annual Report|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/Hypatia-annual-report-2018-final.pdf|journal=Hypatia|volume=|pages=|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n\n\u25cf [http://www.phil.bilkent.edu.tr/index.php/sandrine-berges/ Sandrine Berg\u00e8s] and [http://www.phil.bilkent.edu.tr/index.php/saniye-vatansever/ Saniye Vatansever] ([[Bilkent University]]) for \u201c[https://swip-tr.weebly.com/ Supporting Women in Philosophy in Turkey]\u201d a multi-part project including a student conference, mentoring, workshop, and speaker series. The conference was hosted by the [https://swip-tr.weebly.com/ Society for Women in Philosophy in Turkey (SWIP-TR)].\n\n\u25cf [https://pages.uncc.edu/andrea-pitts/ Andrea Pitts] ([[University of North Carolina at Charlotte|UNC Charlotte]]) and [https://www.american.edu/cas/faculty/pzurn.cfm Perry Zurn] ([[American University]]), \u201c[https://transphilproject.wordpress.com/upcoming-conference/ Trans Philosophy Project],\u201d for a multi-faceted project including a trans philosophy conference, a trans resource initiative including [https://transphilproject.wordpress.com/trans-affirming-practices-in-the-profession/ best practices in the profession] and a trans philosophy [https://transphilproject.wordpress.com/trans-philosophy-bibliographies/ bibliography]. The conference was also support by the [https://www.apaonline.org/ American Philosophical Association].\n\n\u25cf [https://philosophy.la.psu.edu/people/nat3 Nancy Tuana] and [http://philosophy.la.psu.edu/directory/eqv5073 Emma Velez] (both [[Pennsylvania State University|Penn State University]]), \u201c[http://sites.psu.edu/lugonesconference/ Toward Decolonial Feminisms],\u201d partial support for conference speakers.\n\nFour Individual Grants were awarded to graduate students for conference papers that contribute to diversifying feminist philosophy or philosophy in general, including:\n\n\u25cf [https://kwanjonathan.wordpress.com/ Jonathan Kwan] ([[City University of New York|CUNY]])\n\n\u25cf [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Rebecca_Monteleone Rebecca Monteleone] ([[Arizona State University]]) \n\n\u25cf Val\u00e9rie Simon ([[University of Oregon]])\n\n\u25cf [https://research.utu.fi/converis/portal/Person/964146;jsessionid=3831e47b83aef2bd1975f75f4425?lang=en_GB Tiia Sudenkaarne] ([[University of Turku]])\n\nIn 2019, the grant application process was postponed to allow for the finalization of the journal\u2019s revised governance structure. Applications are scheduled to reopen in 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/announcements/diversity-grants-postponed-until-2020/|title=Diversity Grants Postponed Until 2020|date=2019-05-28|website=hypatia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>.\n\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Since 2013, Hypatia has awarded a Diversity Essay Prize biannually to acknowledge outstanding scholarship written by a graduate student, postdoctoral fellow, or non-tenured faculty member who embodies a feminist, intersectional approach in a philosophical analysis combining categories of identity (e.g. gender, class, disability, ethnicity, nationality, race, religion, sexuality).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/category/annual-reports/|title=annual reports Archives|website=hypatia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Most recently, in 2018, the Diversity Essay prize was awarded to:\n\n\u25cf [http://www.filosoficas.unam.mx/sitio/aso-aurorageorginabustosarellano150 Aurora Georgina Bustos Arellano] ([[National Autonomous University of Mexico|Universidad Nacional Aut\u00f3noma de M\u00e9xico]])\n\n\u25cf Fulden Ibrahimhakkioglu ([[Middle East Technical University|Middle East Technical University, Turkey]])\n\n\u25cf [https://kwanjonathan.wordpress.com/ Jonathan Kwan] ([[City University of New York|CUNY]])\n\n\u25cf [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Rebecca_Monteleone Rebecca Monteleone] ([[Arizona State University|Arizona State]])\n\n\u25cf [https://hpi.uq.edu.au/profile/463/laura-roberts Laura Roberts] ([[University of Queensland|Univ of Queensland, Australia]])\n\n\u25cf Valerie Simon ([[University of Oregon|Univ of Oregon]])\n\n\u25cf [https://research.utu.fi/converis/portal/Person/964146;jsessionid=3831e47b83aef2bd1975f75f4425?lang=en_GB Tiia Sudenkaarne] ([[University of Turku|Univ of Turku]], [[Finland]])\n<br />\n==Abstracting and indexing==\n''Hypatia'' is [[abstracting and indexing|abstracted and indexed]] in the following [[bibliographic databases]]:<ref>{{cite web<!--Citation bot deny--> |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001/homepage/ProductInformation.html |title=Overview |work=Hypathia |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell}}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=26em|\n*[[Arts and Humanities Citation Index]]<ref name=ISI>{{cite web |url=http://ip-science.thomsonreuters.com/mjl/ |title=Master Journal List |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |work=Intellectual Property & Science |accessdate=2017-07-25}}</ref>\n*[[Current Contents]]/Arts & Humanities<ref name=ISI/>\n*Current Contents/Social & Behavioral Sciences<ref name=ISI/>\n*[[EBSCO Information Services|EBSCO databases]]\n*[[International Bibliography of Periodical Literature]]\n*[[International Political Science Abstracts]]\n*[[MLA International Bibliography]]\n*[[Philosopher's Index]]\n*[[PhilPapers]]\n*[[ProQuest|ProQuest databases]]\n*[[Scopus]] <ref name=Scopus>{{cite web |url=https://www.scopus.com/sourceid/23699 |title=Source details: Hypatia |publisher=[[Elsevier]] |work=Scopus preview |accessdate=2017-07-25}}</ref>\n*[[Social Science Citation Index]]<ref name=ISI/>\n*[[Sociological Abstracts]]\n}}\nAccording to the ''[[Journal Citation Reports]]'', the journal has a 2017 [[impact factor]] of 0.712.<ref name=WoS>{{cite book |year=2018 |chapter=Hypatia |title=2017 Journal Citation Reports |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |edition=Social Sciences |series=[[Web of Science]]|title-link=Journal Citation Reports }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of women's studies journals]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|26em}}\n\n== Foot Notes ==\n \n# \n\u201cIn 1998, a double\u2010volume special issue thematized multicultural and postcolonial feminist challenges to philosophy and the need for feminists to engage internationally (Narayan and Harding 1998, 13.2, 13.3) and was followed by two additional special issues speaking to these themes (Scholtz 2013, 28.2; Herr and Park 2017, 32.3). Special issues were published on women of color feminism (Dotson 2014, 29.1), feminism and disability (Kittay, Silvers, and Wendell 2001, 16.4; 2002, 17.3; Hall 2015, 30.1), indigenous women (Talamantez, Guerro, and Waters 2003, 18.2), heterosexism (Callahan, Mann, and Ruddick 2007, 22.1), and transgender studies (Bettcher and Garry 2009, 24.3)\u201d (PFF 397)\n#\nCamisha Russell. \u201cOn Black Women, \u2018In Defense of Transracialism,\u2019 and Imperial Harm.\u201d Hypatia, 34.2 (2019).\n  \n#\nCamisha Russell. \u201cOn Black Women, \u2018In Defense of Transracialism,\u2019 and Imperial Harm.\u201d Hypatia, 34.2 (2019). 176-194. Jana Cattien. \u201cAgainst \u2018Transracialism\u2019: Revisiting the Debate.\u201d Hypatia 34.2 (2019). (Early View). Lewis R. Gordon. \u201cThinking Through Rejections of Transracialism.\u201d Philosophy Today, 62.1 (2018). 11-19. Kris Sealey. \u201cTransracialism and White Allyship: A Response to Rebecca Tuvel.\u201d Philosophy Today, 62.1 (2018). 21-29. Tina Fernandes Botts. \u201cRace and Method: The Tuvel Affair.\u201d Philosophy Today, 62.1 (2018). 51-72. Chlo\u00eb Taylor. \u201cOn Intelletual Generosity: A Response to Rebecca Tuvel\u2019s \u2018In Defense of Transracialism\u2019.\u201d Philosophy Today, 62.1 (2018). 3-10. Sabrina Hom. \u201c(Dis)Engaging with Race Theory: Feminist Philosophy\u2019s Debate on Transracialism\u2019 as a Case Study.\u201d Philosophy Today, 62.1 (2018).31-50. Rebecca Tuvel. \u201cRacial Transitions and Controversial Positions: Reply to Taylor, Gordon, Sealey, Hom, and Botts.\u2